<a name="inpress"><h3>In press:</h3></a>

<ol>
<li> (with Jo&atilde;o Ara&uacute;jo) Primitive groups synchronize non-uniform
maps of extreme ranks, <em>J. Combinatorial Theory</em> (B);
doi: <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jctb.2014.01.006">10.1016/j.jctb.2014.01.006</a>, 
arXiv <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1306.4827">1306.4827</a>
<blockquote><p><b>Abstract:</b> Let &Omega; be a set of cardinality <i>n</i>,
<i>G</i> a permutation group on &Omega;, and <i>f</i>:&Omega;&rarr;&Omega;
a map which is not a permutation. We say that <i>G</i> synchronizes <i>f</i>
if the semigroup &lang;<i>G,f</i>&rang; contains a constant map.
</p><p>
The first author has conjectured that a primitive group synchronizes
any map whose kernel is non-uniform. Rystsov proved one instance of this
conjecture, namely, degree <i>n</i>  primitive groups synchronize maps of
rank <i>n</i>&minus;1 (thus, maps with kernel type (2,1,&hellip;,1)). We
prove some extensions of Rystsov's result, including this: a primitive group
synchronizes every map whose kernel type is (<i>k</i>,1,&hellip;,1).
Incidentally this result provides a new characterization of imprimitive groups.
 We also  prove that  the conjecture above holds for maps of extreme ranks,
that is, ranks 3, 4 and <i>n</i>&minus;2.
</p><p>
These proofs use a graph-theoretic
technique due to the second author: a transformation semigroup fails to
contain a constant map if and only if it is contained in the endomorphism
semigroup of a non-null (simple undirected) graph.
</p><p>
The paper finishes with a number of open problems, whose solutions will certainly require very delicate graph theoretical considerations.
</p></blockquote></li>
<li> (with Jo&atilde;o Ara&uacute;jo) Permutation groups and transformation
semigroups: results and problems, Proceedings of Groups St Andrews 2013; arXiv
<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1308.3585">1308.3585</a>
<blockquote><p><b>Abstract:</b> J.M. Howie, the influential St Andrews 
semigroupist, claimed that we value an area of pure mathematics to the
extent that (a) it gives rise to arguments that are deep and elegant, and
(b) it has interesting interconnections with other parts of pure mathematics.
</p><p>
This paper surveys some recent results on the transformation semigroup
generated by a permutation group <i>G</i> and a single non-permutation <i>a</i>.
Our particular concern is the influence that properties of <i>G</i> (related to
homogeneity, transitivity and primitivity) have on the structure of the
semigroup. In the first part of the paper, we consider properties of
<i>S</i>&nbsp;=&nbsp;&lang;<i>G,a</i>&rang; such as regularity and idempotent
generation. The second
is a brief report on the synchronization project, which aims to decide
in what circumstances <i>S</i> contains an element of rank&nbsp;1. The paper
closes with a list of open problems on permutation groups and linear groups,
and some comments about the impact on semigroups are provided.
</p><p>
These two research directions outlined above lead to very interesting and
challenging problems on primitive permutation groups whose solutions require
combining results from several different areas of mathematics, certainly
fulfilling both of Howie's elegance and value tests in a new and fascinating
way.
</p></blockquote></li>
<li> (With Jo&atilde;o Ara&uacute;jo) Two generalizations of homogeneity in
groups with applications to regular semigroups,
<em>Trans. Amer. Math. Soc.</em>; arXiv <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1204.2195">1204.2195</a>
<blockquote><p><b>Abstract:</b>
Let <i>X</i> be a finite set such that |<i>X</i>|&nbsp;=&nbsp;<i>n</i> and let <i>i</i>&le;<i>j</i>&le;<i>n</i>. A group <i>G</i>&le;<i>S<sub>n</sub></i> is said to be (<i>i,j</i>)-homogeneous if for every <i>I,J</i>&sube;<i>X</i>, such that |<i>I</i>|=<i>i</i> and |<i>J</i>|=<i>j</i>, there exists <i>g</i>&isin;<i>G</i> such that <i>Ig</i>&sube;<i>J</i>. (Clearly (<i>i,i</i>)-homogeneity is <i>i</i>-homogeneity in the usual sense.)
</p>
<p>
A group <i>G</i>&le;<i>S<sub>n</sub></i> is said to have the <i>k</i>-universal transversal property if given any set <i>I</i>&sube;<i>X</i> (with |<i>I</i>|=<i>k</i>) and any partition <i>P</i> of <i>X</i> into <i>k</i> blocks, there exists <i>g</i>&isin;<i>G</i> such that <i>Ig</i> is a section for <i>P</i>. (That is, the orbit of each <i>k</i>-subset of <i>X</i> contains a section for each <i>k</i>-partition of <i>X</i>.)
</p>
<p>
In this paper we classify the groups with the <i>k</i>-universal transversal property (with the exception of two classes of 2-homogeneous groups) and the (<i>k</i>&minus;1,<i>k</i>)-homogeneous groups (for 2&lt;<i>k</i>&le;&lfloor;(<i>n</i>+1/2&rfloor;). As a corollary of the classification we prove that a (<i>k</i>&minus;1,<i>k</i>)-homogeneous group is also (<i>k</i>&minus;2,<i>k</i>&minus;1)-homogeneous, with two exceptions; and similarly, but with no exceptions, groups having the <i>k</i>-universal transversal property have the (<i>k</i>&minus;1)-universal transversal property.
</p>
<p>
A corollary of all the previous results is a  classification of  the groups that together with any rank <i>k</i> transformation on <i>X</i> generate a regular semigroup (for 1&le;<i>k</i>&le;&lfloor;(<i>n</i>+1/2)&rfloor;).
</p>
<p>
The paper ends with a number of challenges for experts in number theory, group and/or semigroup theory, linear algebra and matrix theory.
</p>
</blockquote> </li>
</ol>

