<a name="2014"><h3>2014:</h3></a>

<ol>
<li> (with Joshua M. Browning and Ian M. Wanless) Bounds on the number of
small Latin subsquares,
<em>J. Combinatorial Theory</em> (A) <b>124</b> (2014), 41-56; 
doi: <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jcta.2014.01.002">10.1016/j.jcta.2014.01.002</a>
<blockquote><p><b>Abstract:</b>
Let &zeta;(<i>n,m</i>) be the largest number of order <i>m</i> subsquares achieved by any Latin square of order <i>n</i>. We show that &zeta;(<i>n,m</i>)&nbsp;=&nbsp;&Theta;(<i>n</i><sup>3</sup>) if <i>m</i>&nbsp;&isin;&nbsp;{2,3,5} and &zeta;(<i>n,m</i>)&nbsp;=&nbsp;(<i>n</i><sup>4</sup>) if <i>m</i>&nbsp;&isin;&nbsp;{4,6,9,10}. In particular, (1/8)<i>n</i><sup>3</sup>+O(<i>n</i><sup>2</sup>)&nbsp;&le;&nbsp;&zeta;(<i>n</i>,2)&nbsp;&le;&nbsp;(1/4)<i>n</i><sup>3</sup>+O(<i>n</i><sup>2</sup>) and (1/27)<i>n</i><sup>3</sup>+O(<i>n</i><sup>5/2</sup>)&nbsp;&le;&nbsp;&zeta;(<i>n</i>,3)&nbsp;&le;&nbsp;(1/18)<i>n</i><sup>3</sup>+O(<i>n</i><sup>2</sup>) for all <i>n</i>. We find an explicit bound on &zeta;(<i>n</i>,2<sup><i>d</i></sup>) of the form &Theta;(<i>n</i><sup><i>d</i>+2</sup>) and which is achieved only by elementary abelian 2-groups.
</p>
<p>
For a fixed Latin square <i>L</i> let &zeta;*(<i>n,L</i>) be the largest number of subsquares isotopic to <i>L</i> achieved by any Latin square of order <i>n</i>. When <i>L</i> is a cyclic Latin square we show that &zeta;*(<i>n,L</i>)&nbsp;=&nbsp;&Theta;(<i>n</i><sup>3</sup>). For a large class of Latin squares <i>L</i> we show that &zeta;*(<i>n,L</i>)&nbsp;=&nbsp;O(<i>n</i><sup>3</sup>). For any Latin square <i>L</i> we give an &epsilon; in the interval (0,1) such that &zeta;*(<i>n,L</i>)&nbsp;&ge;&nbsp;&Omega;(<i>n</i><sup>2+&epsilon;</sup>). We belive that this bound is achieved for certain squares <i>L</i>.
</p>
</blockquote>
</li>
</ol>

